      "heading": "Maximum Likelihood Estimation: the master recipe",
      "narration": "Suppose the fleet had a thousand ships, Robin says. Then three random captures would probably include some high numbers — the odds that all three fall below one-ninety are one-ninety-over-a-thousand, cubed, about zero-point-seven percent, so our observations would be a bizarre coincidence. Now suppose the fleet has exactly one-eighty-nine ships — then numbers like ours are perfectly typical. Under which fleet size is what we actually saw most probable? That question — rank all the hypotheses by how well they explain the observed sample — is maximum likelihood estimation. You have data, and a family of models with a knob theta, and MLE says pick the theta under which your observed data would have been most probable. Formally, theta-hat is the argmax over theta of the probability of the data given theta, which we rewrite as the argmax of the sum of log-probabilities of each data point. We maximize the log rather than the raw likelihood for two reasons: it does not change the argmax, since log is increasing, but it turns products of tiny numbers into sums, which is kind both to the algebra and to floating point. Here is the coin example, fully worked. You flip ten times and see seven heads. The model: heads with probability p. The likelihood is p-to-the-seven times one-minus-p-to-the-three, and its log is seven log-p plus three log-one-minus-p. Differentiate using last lesson's tool and set it to zero: seven-over-p minus three-over-one-minus-p equals zero, which gives p-hat equals zero-point-seven. The intuitive answer, now derived rather than assumed — and the exact same calculus works when theta is a billion weights instead of one number. Now the payoff that reorganizes everything you will learn after this. Assume regression with Gaussian noise on the errors, and the log-likelihood of each point becomes minus the residual squared over two-sigma-squared, plus a constant — so maximizing it is exactly minimizing the mean squared error. MSE is not a convention handed down from nowhere; it is maximum likelihood wearing a work uniform. For classification, the model outputs a probability per class, and maximizing the log-probability of the true labels is exactly minimizing cross-entropy — same story. And LLM pretraining in Part Six maximizes the sum of log-probability of each next token given its context, over trillions of tokens. GPT's training objective is literally Robin's coin derivation at cosmic scale.",
