      "narration": "Two statistical ideas close this lesson, and both are interview staples. First, correlation versus causation. The Pearson correlation coefficient r, ranging from minus one to plus one, measures the linear co-movement of two variables, and it is genuinely useful — but it is famously not causation. Ice-cream sales correlate with drownings, not because ice cream drowns people, but because summer causes both. Models trained on observational data learn correlations, full stop; a model will happily learn that hospital visits predict death, and other confounded patterns, because it only sees what moves together. Knowing when a correlation actually supports an intervention — if we change X, will Y move — requires either a real experiment, an A-B test, or careful causal reasoning. Sheldon shows the difference: he does not merely observe that Penny is quieter on chocolate days and declare victory, because that correlation could mean anything, maybe she buys chocolate on already-calm days. Instead he runs an intervention, handing her a chocolate every time she behaves correctly, and her behavior shifts measurably — by controlling the variable rather than passively recording it, he isolates the causal arrow, to Leonard's horror. The one-sentence answer interviewers respect: my model predicts well under the data distribution it saw, but acting on it changes that distribution. Second, the train-test split, restated as statistics rather than convention. Evaluating on training data measures only how well you fit this particular sample, and by Bessel's lesson it always does so optimistically. Evaluating on held-out data estimates performance on the population, which is the thing you actually care about. And here is the trap: if you touch the test set repeatedly while making decisions — choosing hyperparameters, architectures, when to stop — it silently becomes training data, and your estimate inflates. That is why serious work uses three splits, train, validation, and test, and touches the test set exactly once, at the very end. This is not ritual or Kaggle superstition; it is unbiased estimation, the same principle as Bessel's correction operating at the scale of your whole pipeline.",
